  {
    "page": 17,
    "block_id": "page_017:block_051",
    "block_type": "text",
    "text": "For example, SemFuzz [ 47 ] proposes and develops a methodology fundamentally rooted in program semantics, which is precisely architected for the automated synthesis of functional Proof- of-Concept (PoC) exploit code, then repurposes the synthetically generated PoCs as seed inputs to direct a subsequent, systematic fuzzing campaign, with the objective of triggering and thereby uncovering latent vulnerabilities embedded within the target software system. PatchFuzz [ 45 ] begins its operation by first identifying the precise Git commits that are documented as fixes for specific security flaws, then proceeds to extract the associated PoC for each fix, and finally synthesizes this collected information with the semantic and syntactic details of the patch diff to guide focused fuzzing on the modified code regions. TransferFuzz [ 26 ] adopts a trace-guided fuzzing approach wherein it meticulously records and archives the execution traces from a known vulnerable version of the program, subsequently reusing and adapting these historical traces to precisely steer and prioritize its fuzzing campaigns when targeting newer, patched, or derivative versions, thereby systematically determining whether the propagation of reused code components continues to expose the same underlying vulnerability. DeltaFuzz [ 48 ] performs an extraction of version-difference information and strategically utilizes this to prioritize and guide the generation of fuzz inputs along the repair boundary, with the ultimate objective of verifying whether subsequent releases or later versions of the software remain susceptible to the original security flaw. In addition, Directed Greybox Fuzzing (DGF) plays a crucial role in vulnerable version identifica- tion by steering the fuzzer towards specific target sites, such as potentially vulnerable functions. AFLGo [ 11 ] integrates a distance-based metric into the energy scheduling of the fuzzer, prioritizing inputs that execute paths closer to the target vulnerability, thus facilitating the efficient repro- duction of known CVEs across different versions. Building on this, Hawkeye [ 12 ] optimizes the direction mechanism by incorporating static analysis of the call graph and function-level similar- ity, addressing the issue of trace explosion in long-path vulnerability verification. More recently, WindRanger [ 17 ] introduces a deviation-based directed fuzzing approach specifically designed for patch analysis. It identifies deviation basic blocks between the vulnerable and patched versions and directs the fuzzer to explore these divergences, making it highly effective for verifying whether a specific version contains the unpatched logic. To further improve efficiency in large-scale systems, Beacon [ 20 ] utilizes static analysis to compute reachability preconditions and aggressively prunes execution paths that cannot reach the target vulnerability, thereby significantly accelerating the val- idation process. Similarly, SelectFuzz [ 30 ] enables selective fuzzing of specific code regions within complex binaries by isolating the execution of relevant functions, allowing for precise verification of vulnerabilities in targeted components without the overhead of whole-system execution. While dynamic analysis methods produce no false positives, they inherently and unavoidably suffer from the problem of false negatives. This limitation is fundamentally rooted in the stochastic nature of fuzzing techniques, which often struggle to achieve sufficient code coverage or satisfy complex path constraints required to trigger deeply hidden vulnerabilities. Furthermore, estab- lishing, configuring, and maintaining isolated and functionally complete testing environments for every distinct library version or dependency encountered in a large-scale system proves to be impractical, thereby imposing significant scalability constraints on the broader application of this methodology.",
    "bbox": [
      45.349998474121094,
      83.43709564208984,
      441.8588562011719,
      575.412353515625
    ],
    "reading_order": 51,
